@70   = ~Letter~
@71   = ~Mulahey,

we have observed your efforts for quite a while now and are very impressed. A collaboration between you and our organization would prove to be profitable in the long run. If you want to get in touch with us, then meet our contact Tarasch Blackhelmet in Beregost at night. He is waiting at the stone pillar in the center of the city for you.

To God all glory and all jewels to the Serpent!~
@72   = ~Tarash,

Now it's official. Bashrik Sparklehammer has traveled to the Sword Coast! That damned Do-Gooder will ruin us all. According to our information, he and this elf bitch travel from Baldur's Gate to the south... when he arrives at the crossroads to Lion's Way, we will give him a proper surprise!

To God all glory and all the jewels to the Serpent!~
@73   = ~Pamphlet~
@74   = ~Dwarves of the upper world!

We know how you feel! The Longgrown do nothing but pull a fast one on your beard, the Pointy-ears laugh at you and the Subsurfacers have turned away from you!

But you are not alone. Father Abbathor cares for his children. Even after Moradin knocks your torch out. Do you want to belong to Abbathor's family? Then come to the Undercellars and ask for Draglon!

To God all glory and all the jewels to the Serpent!~ //"steal you blind" als Idiom kenne ich nicht
@75   = ~Notes~
@76   = ~This bundle of wrapped loose pages seems to summarize the approach of the Serpents of Abbathor to a large extent. Apparently, it was their plan from the beginning to capture an ancient dwarfish device, called Gundmagtor, which in common language means something like 'Caller of Black Souls'. The main strike of the cult seems to focus on Nashkel, and the note '<CHARNAME> has killed Mulahey, mines are free' bodes ill indeed.~
@77   = ~This <PRO_RACE> <CHARNAME> who works for Wostok is making <PRO_HISHER> way here. Take someone of the Furious, and a Herald. The Herald shall take the Gundmagtor and bring it to us while you two wait for <CHARNAME> and take <PRO_HIMHER> to an end. Then come to us so that we can discuss the next steps.

L~
@78   = ~Lugosch, faithful servant!

We welcome your effort to bring the iron mine in Nashkel under your control. However, we do have another concern: keep an eye on <CHARNAME> from Candlekeep. The order comes from the lowest depths and you know what that means.

To God all glory and all jewels to the Serpent!~
@79   = ~Lugosch's diary~
@80   = ~Lugosch Grayshirt has written down his journey from a small cultist to priest of Abbathor with neat handwriting. Every line is full of confidence and arrogance. He describes how the cult took root in Amn and he himself was hired as a henchman to the Lurraxol family in Trademeet. The cult grew and soon migrated to larger cities, only to find itself kept down by the Shadow Thieves in Athkatla. Lugosch, who now had ascended to priesthood, was called away by the cult leaders to descend northwards and continue his work in Baldur's Gate.

The last entries of the book deal with his efforts to get in touch with Mulahey in the mines of Nashkel, describe the rude denial given by the Halforc to the dwarves and his malicious glee when <CHARNAME> freed the mine. Lugosch saw his chance and led a fast strike to incorporate a smoothly running iron mine into the cult.~
@81   = ~Emerson's Notes~
@82   = ~Emerson, the foreman of the Nashkel Mines, has written down his calculations and experience in this messed up cluster of papers. For someone who works in the mining industry, this jumble of information is surely a gold mine. For you, however, the notes are useless.~
@83   = ~Diary~
@84   = ~This book looks very old and has been through a lot. Some pages are torn and others pierced, some singed, and a large part of the book is smeared with blood. Even if you cannot decipher the name of the priest, it seems the old wanderer has gone through a lot - traveling with a group of adventurers, certain conflicts over the 'true' dwarf existence and finally the banishment from his clan. To the dwarf, to whom his family was above all, this loss made him first lose his mind and then drove him straight into the arms of the Serpents.~
@85   = ~Bashrik's Hammer +2~
@86   = ~The priest of Moradin, Bashrik Sparklehammer, was considered as wise and true and within the community of liberal dwarves. He continued to fight against the secession of the surface dwarves and generally relished a high reputation. This hammer, charged with the thunderbolts of Moradin, was his greatest weapon in the fight against evil.

STATISTICS:

Combat Abilities: +1 electricity damage
THAC0: +2 bonus
Damage:  1D4 + 3
Damage type:  crushing
Weight: 5
Speed Factor: 2
Proficiency Type: War Hammer
Type:  1-handed
Requires: 9 Strength
Not Usable By:
 Druid
 Mage 
 Thief~
@87   = ~Bashrik's Journal~
@88   = ~The book is written with neat handwriting and reports the last trip of Bashrik Sparklehammer. Bashrik was on the tail of a cult that calls itself 'The Serpents of Abbathor'. For them, Abbathor, the only evil god among the Morndinsamman, is considered the liberator and saint patron of the dwarfkind of the surface.

You cannot learn much more from the book because apparently, the notes of Bashrik were written primarily for the initiated. Only the last entry could offer a clue, should you want to look into the matter:

'I have departed from Wostok today. Mirjala and I will try our luck south, Wostok will take a look in the big city. We will meet again in the temple of Helm when I have more information.

Addendum: After racking the assassin who awaited us at the Friendly Arm Inn I have learned a name, at least. A certain Draglon appears in the Undercellars to regulate the affairs of the cult. Well, I will delay that until my return.'

(If you want to investigate the cult and what it's about, it will be of advantage to keep this book.)~
@89   = ~Artifact~
@90   = ~Dwarven Artifact~
@91   = ~What this artifact exactly does is unknown to you. The Serpents of Abbathor want it, that's probably sufficient information.~
@92   = ~Gundmagtor~
@93   = ~The history of this artifact lies in darkness. From what you can conjecture from the few scraps that you have learned so far, and if you have interpreted the few ancient dwarven runes that cover the device correctly, this artifact in some way allows you to contact the forefathers of the dwarves and redirect their energy into shadowy beings.

From what you know about the old dwarves, such an act is the greatest sacrilege a dwarf might be capable of. The peace of the dead is sacred and only very corrupted souls would dare to break it.~
